# JavaScript Object Literals 

This document demonstrates creating objects using **object literals** in JavaScript and calculating their area using methods.

---

## Rectangle Object

```javascript
// Create an object called 'rectangle' using an object literal
const rectangle = {
  // 'name' property holds a string value representing the rectangle's name
  name: 'Rectangle 1',
  
  // 'width' property stores the rectangle's width
  width: 20,
  
  // 'height' property stores the rectangle's height
  height: 10,
  
  // 'area' is a method to calculate the area of the rectangle
  // 'this' keyword refers to the object itself, accessing its properties
  area: function () {
    // Multiply width by height and return the result
    return this.width * this.height;
  },
};

// Object literals are ideal for single-use objects. 
// Creating multiple similar objects requires repeating the same structure, 
// which is inefficient. For many similar objects, classes or constructor functions are more appropriate.

const rectangle2 = {
  // Second rectangle object
  name: 'Rectangle 2',
  
  // Width of the second rectangle
  width: 30,
  
  // Height of the second rectangle
  height: 20,
  
  // Method to calculate the area of the second rectangle
  area: function () {
    // 'this.width' and 'this.height' refer to rectangle2's properties
    return this.width * this.height;
  },
};

// Call the area method of the first rectangle and display the result in the console
console.log(rectangle.area()); // Output: 200 (20 * 10)

// Call the area method of the second rectangle and display the result in the console
console.log(rectangle2.area()); // Output: 600 (30 * 20)
